Since C++11 the standard algorithms of [`std::min`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/min) and `std::max` can take an initializer list. So simply pass all 4 variables.

    #include &lt;algorithm&gt;

    auto low = std::min( {v1, v2, v3, v4} );
    auto high = std::min( {v1, v2, v3, v4} );

(Or do it in one statement with [`std::minmax`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/minmax))

You can use this notation by using initializer_list if you can use C++11.
&gt; std::min({var1, var2, var3, var4});

This notation also can realize almost same function without c++11 environment.
&gt; std::min( std::min(var1, var2), std::min(var3, var4) );

std::max also same.

